What is zlog
===================

zlog is a high efficent, thread safe, flexsible, pure c logging library. 

Actually, in the c world there is NO good logging library for application
like logback in java or log4cxx in c++.  printf can work, but can not be
easily redirected or reformat, syslog is slow and designed for kenerl use.

So I write zlog.


Install
===================

If checking out from Git (https://github.com/HardySimpson/zlog):

    $ sh autogen.sh

Then 

    $ ./configure --prefix=[where u wanna install it] --enable-test[compile test program]
    $ make
    $ make install

If --enable-test is used, then run all the test program under
test directory and see output. They are also good example codes
which show how to use zlog

Linking to zlog
===================

If your system has pkgconfig then you can just add this to your makefile

CFLAGS += $(shell pkg-config --cflags zlog)
LDFLAGS += $(shell pkg-config --libs zlog)

Hello world
===================

$cat zlog_hello.c

	#include <stdio.h>
	#include "zlog.h"

	int main(void)
	{
		int rc;
		zlog_category_t *my_cat;

		rc = zlog_init(NULL);
		if (rc) {
			printf("init failed\n");
			return -1;
		}

		my_cat = zlog_get_category("my_cat");
		if (!my_cat) {
			printf("get cat fail\n");
			return -2;
		}

		ZLOG_INFO(my_cat, "hello, zlog");

		zlog_fini();
		return 0;
	}

$cc -c -o zlog_hello.o zlog_hello.c
$cc -o zlog_hello zlog_hello.o -L[path of libzlog.so] -lzlog
$./zlog_hello
hello, zlog

